The overall purpose of the project is to support the government's efforts in increasing access and improving the quality of girls' education through capacity building and targeted interventions at both institutional and community level.


Geographically, the project will target the most disenfranchised and hardest to reach areas of Pakistan where girls' access to primary education are most challenged and has high illiteracy rate of adults particularly among women.

In the face of increasingly protracted conflicts and natural disasters affecting culture and heritage, an Emergency Preparedness and Response programme will be implemented, including coordination and technical backstopping of activities by the CLT Sector (both HQs and FOs), the development of relevant policy, tools and inter-institutional cooperation, as well as communication and resource mobilization. This will also include the management of the Heritage Emergency Fund, a multi-donor account created in 2015 to support the implementation of the above Programme.

Through the 38 C/5 2% funds, financial support will be provided to UNESCO Field Offices engaged in common country programming exercises (CCA/UNDAF and equivalent) through targeted decentralizations, based on a review of budget requests submitted by Field Offices. In addition to ensuring UNESCO's programmatic involvement in CCA/UNDAFs, the 2% funds will also facilitate UNESCO's involvement in UN inter-agency collaboration at the regional level, in particular in Regional UNDG Teams. Furthermore, the 2% funds shall support the development of UNESCO Country Programming Documents (UCPDs), as appropriate.

The World Academy of Sciences (TWAS), for the advancement of science in developing countries, is an international science academy, founded in 1983 in Trieste, Italy, by a distinguished group of scientists from the South under the leadership of the late Nobel laureate Abdus Salam. In 1991, the UNESCO assumed responsibility for administering TWAS funds and personnel. Its main mission is to promote scientific excellence and capacity in the South for science-based sustainable development. All TWAS Programmes (e.g., fellowships, research grants, exchanges prizes) are developed and implemented to build science-capacity and to honor scientific excellence in the South. See www.twas.org.

The agreement contributes to the development of several actions aimed at supporting Brazilian public policies in the fields of education, science and culture. In particular, the Umbrella Cooperation Agreement is a very valuable instrument for UNESCO to strengthen a strategic partnership with the Ministry of Education, especially because it is directly coordinated by the Minister's Executive Office and the Executive Secretary. The activities are designed aiming at supporting national efforts in improving universal access, equity and quality education in all schooling levels. Quality and equity remain a crucial challenge in Brazil as both are essential to respond to the needs of the country.

The Fund for the Elimination of Doping in Sport was established, in 2008, to assist all States Parties with the development and implementation of anti-doping programmes consistent with the Convention. This Fund, established to build anti-doping capacity around the world, can help finance national and regional anti-doping projects in the areas of: (1) education; (2) policy advice; and (3) capacity development.
